              <span id="reviewTextContainer2307001570" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14463205371715701869">The pages just flew by and I realized the book was over. However, there was an epilogue that deserved thinking about. Sidney Sheldon is not a perfect writer. But this book of his is so much better than many bestsellers today.<br/><br/>The author has used sex, action, and loneliness tropes to great effect here. Windmill of the Gods is slightly dated, but you can treat it like a classic, if you want.<br/><br/>The violence in the book is sometimes there, and sometimes it&apos;s hinted at. The fate of the evil mastermind is</span>
  <span id="freeText14463205371715701869" style="display:none">The pages just flew by and I realized the book was over. However, there was an epilogue that deserved thinking about. Sidney Sheldon is not a perfect writer. But this book of his is so much better than many bestsellers today.<br /><br />The author has used sex, action, and loneliness tropes to great effect here. Windmill of the Gods is slightly dated, but you can treat it like a classic, if you want.<br /><br />The violence in the book is sometimes there, and sometimes it's hinted at. The fate of the evil mastermind is terrible, despite his shenanigans. I won't spoil the story in my review. Read it and be thrilled.</span>
